67
00:02:46,350 --> 00:02:48,067
So when I started
researching this,

68
00:02:48,067 --> 00:02:50,400
I thought it was sort of just
a coincidence-- of grammar

69
00:02:50,400 --> 00:02:52,830
of graphics, glamour
of graphics, haha.

70
00:02:52,830 --> 00:02:55,590
But it turns out that the
word glamour is actually

71
00:02:55,590 --> 00:02:57,540
derived from the word grammar.

72
00:02:57,540 --> 00:02:59,880
So back in the Middle
Ages, the word grammar

73
00:02:59,880 --> 00:03:01,410
meant all learning.

74
00:03:01,410 --> 00:03:05,340
And that included things
like magic and occult.

75
00:03:05,340 --> 00:03:08,940
And through the ages, that word
sort of morphed into glamour.

76
00:03:08,940 --> 00:03:11,460
And as it did it lost the
association with knowledge

77
00:03:11,460 --> 00:03:15,900
and it became to mean just
a magical spell actually.

78
00:03:15,900 --> 00:03:18,040
And then eventually,
in the 18th century,

79
00:03:18,040 --> 00:03:20,202
the idea of magic sort of
washed away a little bit.

80
00:03:20,202 --> 00:03:21,660
And we got the
meaning that we know

81
00:03:21,660 --> 00:03:25,260
today which is the sort of
exciting, illusory, romantic

82
00:03:25,260 --> 00:03:27,740
attractiveness.

83
00:03:27,740 --> 00:03:29,570
So the grammar of
graphics is a tool

84
00:03:29,570 --> 00:03:31,370
that enables us to
concisely describe

85
00:03:31,370 --> 00:03:33,295
the components of a graphic.

86
00:03:33,295 --> 00:03:34,670
And what I'm going
to do today is

87
00:03:34,670 --> 00:03:37,730
try to bring this sort of
illusory, romantic quality

88
00:03:37,730 --> 00:03:40,550
of glamour a little bit
closer to a grammar.

89
00:03:40,550 --> 00:03:42,050
So I'm going to
describe a tool that

90
00:03:42,050 --> 00:03:45,865
enables us to concisely describe
the design of a graphic.

91
00:03:45,865 --> 00:03:47,240
So in the grammar
of graphics, we

92
00:03:47,240 --> 00:03:51,800
have these three components of
data aesthetics and geometries

93
00:03:51,800 --> 00:03:53,548
that are really the
core of any chart.

94
00:03:53,548 --> 00:03:54,840
And I know there's more layers.

95
00:03:54,840 --> 00:03:58,202
But this is really the core
of how to describe a chart.

96
00:03:58,202 --> 00:04:00,410
What I'm going to describe
in the glamour of graphics

97
00:04:00,410 --> 00:04:00,950
is similar.

98
00:04:00,950 --> 00:04:03,230
But I'm going to
describe three layers

99
00:04:03,230 --> 00:04:05,820
that you need to describe
the design of a graphic.

100
00:04:05,820 --> 00:04:09,500
And that's the layout, the
typography, and the color.

101
00:04:09,500 --> 00:04:12,390
So beginning with
layout, I'm going

102
00:04:12,390 --> 00:04:14,910
to talk about three
main concepts today.

103
00:04:14,910 --> 00:04:18,570
And that is alignment,
whitespace, and grids, lines,

104
00:04:18,570 --> 00:04:20,430
and borders.

105
00:04:20,430 --> 00:04:22,350
So beginning with
alignment, I want

106
00:04:22,350 --> 00:04:24,540
to talk about titles first.

107
00:04:24,540 --> 00:04:29,430
Titles should be
top-left aligned usually.

108
00:04:29,430 --> 00:04:31,110
And when I say
top-left aligned, I

109
00:04:31,110 --> 00:04:33,908
don't mean the case
that you see on the left

110
00:04:33,908 --> 00:04:35,700
where you have left
aligned with your data.

111
00:04:35,700 --> 00:04:38,850
I mean left aligned all the
way to the edge of your chart

112
00:04:38,850 --> 00:04:41,555
to create a nice clean line
with the edge of your chart.

113
00:04:41,555 --> 00:04:42,930
Now previously,
this was actually

114
00:04:42,930 --> 00:04:44,893
kind of tricky to do
with ggplot but luckily

115
00:04:44,893 --> 00:04:46,310
in the development
version we have

116
00:04:46,310 --> 00:04:50,870
a new argument that makes
this very, very simple to do.

117
00:04:50,870 --> 00:04:54,150
Next I want you
to please not make

118
00:04:54,150 --> 00:04:57,390
me do like this when
I read your chart.

119
00:04:57,390 --> 00:04:59,550
So I see this a lot
of times, especially

120
00:04:59,550 --> 00:05:02,910
in academic graphics where you
have these really long x-axis

121
00:05:02,910 --> 00:05:04,290
labels.

122
00:05:04,290 --> 00:05:05,525
Nobody wants to do that.

123
00:05:05,525 --> 00:05:06,900
So, of course,
it's always better

124
00:05:06,900 --> 00:05:10,193
if you can to flip our
coordinates horizontally.

125
00:05:10,193 --> 00:05:11,610
Or if you can't
manage to flip it,

126
00:05:11,610 --> 00:05:14,160
you can just try to make the
text horizontal by increasing

127
00:05:14,160 --> 00:05:16,118
your spacing and such.

128
00:05:16,118 --> 00:05:17,910
This is a little more
controversial, maybe,

129
00:05:17,910 --> 00:05:19,980
but I also think it's
actually best practice

130
00:05:19,980 --> 00:05:23,220
not to use vertical
axis labels because you

131
00:05:23,220 --> 00:05:24,292
have the same problem.

132
00:05:24,292 --> 00:05:25,500
So you can do the same thing.

133
00:05:25,500 --> 00:05:27,900
You can try to make the
text just horizontal.

134
00:05:27,900 --> 00:05:31,500
Or a lot of times you can get
rid of axis labels entirely.

135
00:05:31,500 --> 00:05:34,050
A lot of axis labels are
completely unnecessary-- things

136
00:05:34,050 --> 00:05:35,010
like dates.

137
00:05:35,010 --> 00:05:36,960
In this case, SUV, minivan--

138
00:05:36,960 --> 00:05:39,500
it's obvious these
are types of cars.

139
00:05:39,500 --> 00:05:41,730
And usually by just
including a good title,

140
00:05:41,730 --> 00:05:43,575
you can do away
with axis labels.

141
00:05:45,543 --> 00:05:47,210
So when you're thinking
about alignment,

142
00:05:47,210 --> 00:05:51,260
you should always try to create
clean lines and symmetry.

143
00:05:51,260 --> 00:05:53,390
And what I want to go
over is a little bit--

144
00:05:53,390 --> 00:05:55,460
this graphic from 538
that I think really

145
00:05:55,460 --> 00:05:57,660
illustrates some
of these points.

146
00:05:57,660 --> 00:05:59,400
So this doesn't have
big blocks of text.

147
00:05:59,400 --> 00:06:01,850
But just to mention, if you
do have big blocks of text

148
00:06:01,850 --> 00:06:03,680
like an infographic
or something,

149
00:06:03,680 --> 00:06:05,990
you want to left align
those most likely.

150
00:06:05,990 --> 00:06:09,410
Left alignment should
sort of be your default.

151
00:06:09,410 --> 00:06:12,590
Right alignment can be used
for labels a lot of times,

152
00:06:12,590 --> 00:06:14,720
so especially like
horizontal bar labels where

153
00:06:14,720 --> 00:06:16,280
the goal is to
create a clean line

154
00:06:16,280 --> 00:06:19,040
with the edge of your data.

155
00:06:19,040 --> 00:06:21,320
And sometimes
subtitles or labels

156
00:06:21,320 --> 00:06:23,810
can be center aligned if
it helps to create symmetry

157
00:06:23,810 --> 00:06:25,657
within the graphic.

158
00:06:25,657 --> 00:06:27,740
So in this case, you can
see actually the designer

159
00:06:27,740 --> 00:06:29,753
made a mistake on the 2014 one.

160
00:06:29,753 --> 00:06:30,920
It should be center aligned.

161
00:06:30,920 --> 00:06:32,858
But it's slightly off center.

162
00:06:32,858 --> 00:06:34,650
But if you look at the
rest of the graphic,

163
00:06:34,650 --> 00:06:37,323
you can see how this left
alignment, right alignment,

164
00:06:37,323 --> 00:06:39,740
and center alignment sort of
creates this perfect symmetry

165
00:06:39,740 --> 00:06:40,532
within the graphic.

166
00:06:42,860 --> 00:06:46,100
So charts often come with
these extraneous elements.

167
00:06:46,100 --> 00:06:47,360
They're not data.

168
00:06:47,360 --> 00:06:50,310
And a lot of times, they
can distract from the chart.

169
00:06:50,310 --> 00:06:53,750
So I want to talk a little
bit about how to reduce those.

170
00:06:53,750 --> 00:06:55,790
A good example of
this is borders.

171
00:06:55,790 --> 00:06:58,397
You almost never need
a border in a chart.

172
00:06:58,397 --> 00:07:00,230
Oftentimes, they just
don't serve a purpose.

173
00:07:00,230 --> 00:07:02,300
And all they do is
distract from your data--

174
00:07:02,300 --> 00:07:05,220
add ink to the page.

175
00:07:05,220 --> 00:07:07,580
Another thing is grid lines.

176
00:07:07,580 --> 00:07:08,960
I understand that
there's reasons

177
00:07:08,960 --> 00:07:10,820
to have grid lines sometimes.

178
00:07:10,820 --> 00:07:12,600
But I encourage you
to always question

179
00:07:12,600 --> 00:07:13,910
the purpose of every grid line.

180
00:07:13,910 --> 00:07:16,370
Do you need horizontal
grid lines in every case?

181
00:07:16,370 --> 00:07:18,750
Do you need minor grid lines?

182
00:07:18,750 --> 00:07:21,080
If not, please remove them.

183
00:07:21,080 --> 00:07:22,970
If you do need them,
I encourage you

184
00:07:22,970 --> 00:07:25,897
to make them as light
and as small as possible

185
00:07:25,897 --> 00:07:27,980
so that they sort of
disappear into the background

186
00:07:27,980 --> 00:07:31,278
rather than distracting
from your data.

187
00:07:31,278 --> 00:07:33,320
Another thing that distracts
from your data a lot

188
00:07:33,320 --> 00:07:35,210
is legends,
particularly when you

189
00:07:35,210 --> 00:07:38,300
have like a big blob of a legend
off to the right-hand side

190
00:07:38,300 --> 00:07:39,527
of your chart.

191
00:07:39,527 --> 00:07:41,360
It's not a very good
flow within your chart.

192
00:07:41,360 --> 00:07:42,872
So I recommend, if
you have legends,

193
00:07:42,872 --> 00:07:44,330
you put them right
below the titles

194
00:07:44,330 --> 00:07:47,240
where it creates a nice
flow with your chart.

195
00:07:47,240 --> 00:07:50,960
A better solution even is
to directly label your data.

196
00:07:50,960 --> 00:07:54,410
Or my favorite solution
is to use colored text

197
00:07:54,410 --> 00:07:58,100
to indicate your
legend in the title.

198
00:07:58,100 --> 00:08:00,590
And this will now be possible
with the new gridtext

199
00:08:00,590 --> 00:08:05,450
package, which I think Claus is
talking about this afternoon.

200
00:08:05,450 --> 00:08:09,013
So a few words about whitespace.

201
00:08:09,013 --> 00:08:10,430
This is particularly
relevant when

202
00:08:10,430 --> 00:08:13,010
you're looking at things like
dashboards and infographics

203
00:08:13,010 --> 00:08:15,510
where you're laying out
a lot of charts together.

204
00:08:15,510 --> 00:08:16,970
And what I often
see is people want

205
00:08:16,970 --> 00:08:19,310
to cram as much information
as they can possibly

206
00:08:19,310 --> 00:08:21,300
get onto the page.

207
00:08:21,300 --> 00:08:23,630
But what that ends
up resulting in

208
00:08:23,630 --> 00:08:26,730
is that you can't even
understand any of it.

209
00:08:26,730 --> 00:08:29,070
Your eye has no idea
where to go on the page.

210
00:08:29,070 --> 00:08:32,130
And so your charts really
need room to breathe.

211
00:08:32,130 --> 00:08:34,070
So I always recommend
it's like garlic--

212
00:08:34,070 --> 00:08:36,440
you take as much white
space as you think you need,

213
00:08:36,440 --> 00:08:37,340
and then triple it.

214
00:08:39,950 --> 00:08:41,900
So that's sort of the
foundation of building

215
00:08:41,900 --> 00:08:43,880
a nice chart is the layout.

216
00:08:43,880 --> 00:08:47,620
And next up, I'm going
