334
00:13:37,277 --> 00:13:39,400
And I want to highlight
the HSL color space.

335
00:13:39,400 --> 00:13:42,390
So this is a way of
describing color in contrast

336
00:13:42,390 --> 00:13:44,030
to something like RGB.

337
00:13:44,030 --> 00:13:46,800
HSL stands for the hue,
saturation, and lightness

338
00:13:46,800 --> 00:13:47,920
of a color.

339
00:13:47,920 --> 00:13:49,770
So the hue is the
actual color itself--

340
00:13:49,770 --> 00:13:51,710
red, green, blue.

341
00:13:51,710 --> 00:13:55,440
The saturation is the amount
of color you have there.

342
00:13:55,440 --> 00:13:58,800
And the lightness is how
light or dark a color is.

343
00:13:58,800 --> 00:14:01,320
So this is an example
where we have a red hue.

344
00:14:01,320 --> 00:14:02,977
And if we turn
down the saturation

345
00:14:02,977 --> 00:14:05,310
you can see that it'll basically
drain all the color out

346
00:14:05,310 --> 00:14:05,810
of there.

347
00:14:05,810 --> 00:14:06,825
It's very dull.

348
00:14:06,825 --> 00:14:08,910
If we turn up the
saturation, it's

349
00:14:08,910 --> 00:14:11,970
going to become very
rich and vibrant.

350
00:14:11,970 --> 00:14:13,622
And if we turn
down the lightness,

351
00:14:13,622 --> 00:14:15,330
we can see we still
have a richness here.

352
00:14:15,330 --> 00:14:17,790
But now it's much darker.

353
00:14:17,790 --> 00:14:21,110
And if we turn it up, it'll
become more lighter obviously.

354
00:14:21,110 --> 00:14:23,130
But you can see how this
is a very easy way when

355
00:14:23,130 --> 00:14:24,720
you pick a color and
you say, oh but I

356
00:14:24,720 --> 00:14:26,970
wish it were a little bit
lighter or a little bit more

357
00:14:26,970 --> 00:14:28,230
saturated or less saturated.

358
00:14:28,230 --> 00:14:30,000
This is a much more
intuitive mental model

359
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:32,220
I think of how to
adjust your colors.

360
00:14:32,220 --> 00:14:33,720
And there's lots
